5000|$|The Strasbourg, {{flagship}} of the [...] "High Seas Forces", nearly {{never even}} went to sea, due to the stringent restriction of fuel, but she was eventually sent to cover, in November 1940, with four cruisers and some destroyers, {{the return of the}} Provence to Toulon. In 1941, she received three more single 13.2 mm Browning CAS MG, and was fitted in 1942 with a <b>détecteur</b> électro-magnétique, the French predecessor of a sea and air warning radar.|$|E
50|$|She received, in 1941, {{three more}} single 13.2 mm Browning CAS MG, and was fitted in 1942, with a {{so-called}} <b>détecteur</b> électro-magnétique, French ancestor {{of a sea}} and air warning radar. Four small rectangular antennæ were fitted atop the main yards of the fore tower, the starboard fore and the port after antennæ were for transmission, the other pair for reception, a different arrangement of the one fitted on Richelieu at Dakar, in 1941. Early tests indicated a range against aircraft of 50 km.|$|E
